      {
        "heading": "Beaconing: The Rhythm That Gives C2 Away",
        "content": "Beaconing is the periodic check-in behavior described above, viewed from the network. It is the single most reliable behavioral tell of an active C2 channel, because it is a direct consequence of how implants are built. An implant sleeps for a configured interval, wakes, connects, and sleeps again. Plotted over time, those connection timestamps form an almost perfectly even sequence: connect at 12:00:00, 12:01:00, 12:02:00, and so on. That regularity is profoundly unnatural.\n\n### Why human traffic is bursty\n\nWhen a person browses the web, their traffic is bursty and clustered. Loading a single news article triggers dozens of near-simultaneous requests (images, scripts, ads, trackers), then silence while they read, then another burst when they click a link. The time between connections to any given server varies wildly — sometimes milliseconds apart, sometimes minutes. Legitimate automated traffic (software updates, telemetry) does have some regularity, but it is usually low-frequency, well-known, and destined for vendor infrastructure you can allow-list. A workstation connecting to an unfamiliar destination every 60 seconds, on the dot, for eight straight hours is not a human and is not your patch agent.\n\n### Fixed interval plus jitter\n\nAttackers know beaconing is detectable, so they add jitter — a random percentage applied to the sleep interval to blur the rhythm. With a 60-second sleep and 30% jitter, check-ins land randomly between 42 and 78 seconds. This defeats naive detections that look for an exact fixed period. But jitter has limits: it widens the distribution of intervals, yet the distribution stays tight and centered compared to genuine human traffic. Even with heavy jitter, a beacon's inter-connection times cluster around a mean far more tightly than real browsing ever does.\n\n### Detecting via time-delta standard deviation\n\nThe robust way to hunt beacons is statistical. For each communicating pair — group by source IP, destination IP, and destination port — sort the connection timestamps and compute the delta (time gap) between each consecutive pair. Then calculate the mean and standard deviation of those deltas. A beacon has a low standard deviation relative to its mean; the ratio stdev/mean (the coefficient of variation) is small, often below 0.2 even with jitter. Human traffic produces a coefficient of variation well above 1. Add supporting signals to cut false positives: a high connection count over a long window, tightly clustered payload sizes (the POST bodies are all roughly the same size), and a destination that is rare in your environment. The combination of low timing variance, consistent byte sizes, and an unfamiliar destination is a high-fidelity beacon. Beware two false-positive sources: legitimate polling apps (NTP, monitoring agents, CRL/OCSP checks) which you allow-list, and connections with too few samples to be statistically meaningful, which you filter out with a minimum-count threshold.",
        "codeExample": "// Splunk SPL: Beaconing hunt via time-delta standard deviation\n// Groups by (src, dst, port), measures how regular the check-in interval is.\n// Low coefficient of variation (stdev/mean) = machine-like rhythm = candidate beacon.\nindex=network sourcetype=zeek:conn\n| sort 0 id.orig_h id.resp_h id.resp_p _time\n| streamstats current=f last(_time) as prev_time by id.orig_h id.resp_h id.resp_p\n| eval delta = _time - prev_time\n| where isnotnull(delta)\n| stats count as connections\n        avg(delta) as mean_interval\n        stdev(delta) as stdev_interval\n        avg(orig_bytes) as avg_bytes_out\n        stdev(orig_bytes) as stdev_bytes_out\n        by id.orig_h id.resp_h id.resp_p\n| where connections > 30 AND mean_interval > 20 AND mean_interval < 3600\n| eval cv_interval = stdev_interval / mean_interval        // coefficient of variation\n| eval cv_bytes = stdev_bytes_out / avg_bytes_out\n| where cv_interval < 0.2 AND cv_bytes < 0.3               // tight timing AND tight sizes\n| sort cv_interval\n| table id.orig_h id.resp_h id.resp_p connections mean_interval cv_interval cv_bytes avg_bytes_out\n// MITRE: T1071 Application Layer Protocol. Allow-list NTP/monitoring/OCSP before alerting."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Common C2 Channels and Their Fingerprints",
        "content": "Each C2 transport leaves a distinct fingerprint. Knowing them lets you pivot from 'something is beaconing' to 'here is exactly what it is and how to confirm it.'\n\n### HTTPS C2 (T1071.001)\n\nHTTPS is the dominant channel because port 443 outbound is nearly universal and TLS hides the payload. But TLS does not hide everything. The TLS Client Hello — the first message a client sends — reveals the exact set of ciphers, extensions, and elliptic curves the client library supports. Hashing those fields produces a JA3 fingerprint that is specific to the TLS implementation, not the destination. Cobalt Strike's default stager, Sliver, and many Go-based implants have documented JA3 values you can match against feeds like abuse.ch SSLBL. Even without a known-bad match, a JA3 that is rare in your environment (99% of your traffic uses a dozen common JA3s, and one host produces a unique one) is worth a look. Also inspect the User-Agent on plaintext HTTP and the SNI/certificate: self-signed certs, certificates with nonsensical subject fields, freshly registered SNI domains, and User-Agents that claim to be Chrome but omit standard headers are all tells. Pair any of these with the originating process from EDR — an outbound 443 connection from rundll32.exe or a random temp-path binary rather than a browser is a screaming indicator.\n\n### DNS tunneling (T1071.004)\n\nWhen HTTPS is blocked or monitored, attackers fall back to DNS, which almost every network permits. DNS C2 encodes data into the subdomain labels of a query: the implant sends 'a1b2c3d4e5f6...encoded-data.attacker.com' and the response (often a TXT or NULL record) carries the tasking back. The fingerprints are unmistakable once you know them: abnormally long query names (100+ characters vs. a normal short domain), high entropy in the subdomain (random-looking consonant-and-digit strings), a high count of unique subdomains under a single parent domain, and heavy use of TXT, NULL, or CNAME record types where A/AAAA should dominate. Aggregate DNS by source and parent domain, look at the 95th-percentile query length and the type distribution, and DNS tunneling stands out sharply.\n\n### Domain fronting and SaaS abuse\n\nSome evasive actors historically used domain fronting: the TLS SNI and HTTP Host header point at different domains, so the connection appears (in SNI) to go to a trusted CDN like a major cloud provider, while the encrypted Host header routes it to the attacker's backend on that same CDN. Since around 2018, most major CDN and cloud providers (Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Google, Microsoft Azure Front Door) have blocked this by enforcing SNI/Host consistency at the edge, so classic domain fronting is far less viable today than older write-ups suggest — you may still encounter it against smaller or misconfigured CDNs. The underlying idea (hide behind a trusted destination) lives on in the far more common technique of abusing legitimate SaaS platforms directly for C2: Slack, Discord, Telegram, Microsoft Teams/Graph API, and Google Drive are current favorites because the destination itself is genuinely trusted, not merely disguised as such. Detection of any residual fronting looks for mismatches between SNI and the decrypted Host header (where TLS inspection exists) and for large or beaconing flows to CDN edge IPs from processes that should not be talking to them. For direct SaaS abuse, the destination is legitimately trusted, so you fall back to behavior — beaconing rhythm, byte ratios, and the originating process — rather than reputation.",
        "codeExample": "// Splunk SPL: DNS tunneling fingerprint hunt (T1071.004)\n// Long, high-entropy subdomains + TXT/NULL types + many uniques under one parent.\nindex=network sourcetype=zeek:dns\n| eval subdomain = mvindex(split(query, \".\"), 0)\n| eval q_len = len(query)\n| eval sub_len = len(subdomain)\n// crude entropy proxy: run of consonants/digits with no vowels\n| eval looks_random = if(match(subdomain, \"[bcdfghjklmnpqrstvwxz0-9]{10,}\"), 1, 0)\n| stats count as total\n        dc(query) as unique_queries\n        max(q_len) as max_len\n        avg(q_len) as avg_len\n        sum(looks_random) as random_hits\n        values(qtype_name) as qtypes\n        by id.orig_h parent_domain\n| where max_len > 80 AND unique_queries > 50 AND avg_len > 40\n| sort - unique_queries\n| table id.orig_h parent_domain total unique_queries max_len avg_len random_hits qtypes\n// Cross-check: TXT/NULL heavy? subdomains high-entropy? destination not your mail/SaaS provider?"
      },
      {
        "heading": "Staging and Exfiltration: How Data Actually Leaves",
        "content": "Command-and-control is the means; exfiltration is usually the end. Understanding how data physically leaves an environment lets you catch a breach at its most consequential moment. Exfiltration is rarely a single action — it is a short pipeline of collection, staging, packaging, and transfer, and each stage is detectable.\n\n### Collection and staging\n\nFirst the attacker gathers what they want. This is the Collection tactic (TA0009): copying files from shares, dumping a database, harvesting email, screen-grabbing. The gathered data is usually written to a staging directory (T1074) — a single location on a compromised host where everything is consolidated before it goes out. Common staging spots are temp directories, a user's AppData, a hidden folder, or a Recycle Bin path. On the host, EDR and file-audit logs show a burst of file reads across many directories converging into writes in one place. That fan-in pattern — many sources, one destination folder, in a short window — is a strong collection signal.\n\n### Compression and archiving\n\nBefore sending, attackers almost always compress and often encrypt the staged data (T1560). Compression shrinks the transfer (faster, less conspicuous volume) and archiving bundles many files into one for a clean single upload. You will see rar.exe, 7z.exe, or a PowerShell Compress-Archive spawning, frequently with a password flag, producing a large .rar/.zip/.7z in the staging directory. Attackers sometimes rename the archive or change its extension to disguise it, so hunt on file-write events for large newly created files and on process creation for archiving utilities — especially when the parent process is unusual (an Office app or a script spawning 7z is far more suspicious than a user double-clicking WinRAR).\n\n### The transfer itself\n\nNow the data moves, and there are three main routes you must distinguish:\n\n**Exfil over C2 (T1041)** — the data goes out the same channel the implant already uses. This is convenient for the attacker and stealthy because it reuses an established connection. The tell is that an otherwise low-volume beacon suddenly ships a large payload: the byte ratio inverts and outbound volume spikes on a connection you may already have flagged as beaconing.\n\n**Exfil over alternative protocol (T1048)** — the attacker opens a separate channel: DNS tunneling for slow trickle exfil, FTP/SFTP, SMTP, or raw sockets to an attacker server. Watch for protocols leaving the environment that this host or user never normally uses, and for DNS volume spikes consistent with tunneling.\n\n**Exfil to cloud storage (T1567)** — increasingly common, the attacker uploads to a service they control: a personal Dropbox/Google Drive/Box account, an attacker-owned S3 bucket, or a pastebin. Because the destination is a reputable SaaS domain, reputation-based blocking fails. You detect it by volume and context: a large upload to a personal cloud account from a corporate host, especially off-hours, especially by a user or department that has no business reason to. CASB and DLP telemetry are your friends here.\n\nAcross all three, the constant is data leaving — so your detections anchor on volume, byte ratio, destination novelty, and timing rather than on any single protocol.",
        "codeExample": "// Attack pipeline mapped to detectable artifacts (host + network)\n//\n// STAGE            TECHNIQUE   ARTIFACT TO HUNT\n// ---------------  ----------  --------------------------------------------\n// Collection       T1074       fan-in: many file reads -> writes in one dir\n// Archive/compress T1560       7z.exe/rar.exe/Compress-Archive w/ password;\n//                              large new .zip/.rar/.7z in staging path\n// Exfil over C2    T1041       beacon flow suddenly ships large payload;\n//                              byte ratio inverts on known-beacon tuple\n// Exfil alt proto  T1048       host uses FTP/SMTP/DNS-tunnel it never uses\n// Exfil to cloud   T1567       large upload to personal Dropbox/Drive/S3,\n//                              off-hours, from a host with no business need\n//\n// Windows process-creation hunt (Sysmon EID 1 / EDR): suspicious archiving\n// | where process_name IN (\"7z.exe\",\"rar.exe\",\"WinRAR.exe\")\n//   AND (command_line LIKE \"%-p%\" OR command_line LIKE \"%-hp%\")   // password\n//   AND parent_process NOT IN (\"explorer.exe\")                    // not user-driven\n// Pair with a file-write event for a >100MB archive in a temp/AppData path."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Detecting Exfil: Byte Ratios, Volume, Destinations, and DLP — What to Ask",
        "content": "You cannot inspect every byte leaving your enterprise, so exfil detection is about asking the right statistical questions of flow and proxy data and letting anomalies surface. Four questions do most of the work.\n\n### Is the byte ratio inverted?\n\nNormal client behavior is download-heavy: you browse, stream, and pull far more data in than you push out. So bytes_in is normally much greater than bytes_out. Exfiltration inverts this — the client ships a large volume out and receives little back. Compute the ratio bytes_out / bytes_in per session, aggregated by source and destination, and flag sessions where outbound dwarfs inbound (say ratio > 10) and the absolute outbound volume is large (tens or hundreds of MB). The ratio matters because it filters out large legitimate downloads; the absolute floor filters out small chatty flows that happen to be outbound-heavy. Together they isolate real bulk egress. The question to ask: is this host sending far more than it receives, to somewhere it has no reason to?\n\n### Is this destination new?\n\nAttackers exfil to infrastructure your environment has never talked to before. Maintain a baseline of destinations each host or department normally reaches, and treat first-contact destinations carrying large volume as suspicious. A finance workstation that has never once connected to a given IP or domain suddenly uploading 4 GB to it is a near-certain incident. Newly registered domains and personal cloud accounts are especially high-signal. The question: have we ever seen this host talk to this place before, and if not, why now and why so much?\n\n### Is the timing wrong?\n\nAttackers often move data when nobody is watching — nights, weekends, holidays. Establish per-host and per-user baselines of normal active hours and byte volume, then flag large transfers that fall well outside them. A 2 a.m. Saturday upload from a machine whose user works 9-to-5 weekdays is worth waking up for. The question: is this volume happening at a time this entity is normally idle?\n\n### What does DLP and CASB say?\n\nFlow data tells you volume and destination; DLP and CASB tell you content and channel. DLP fires when sensitive data types (credit-card numbers, source code, classified documents) cross a monitored boundary — email, web upload, USB, print, cloud sync. CASB surfaces uploads to personal or unsanctioned cloud accounts. When a byte-ratio or off-hours anomaly lines up with a DLP hit on the same host and time window, you have moved from 'suspicious flow' to 'confirmed sensitive-data egress.' The question: does content-aware telemetry confirm that what left was actually sensitive?\n\n### Putting it together\n\nNo single signal is decisive — a large upload could be a legitimate backup, a new destination could be a new vendor, off-hours could be a scheduled job. Seniority is in the correlation. When an inverted byte ratio, a brand-new destination, an off-hours window, and a DLP hit converge on one host, you are not guessing anymore. Always output your pivot fields — source IP, user, destination, volume, timestamp — so the next analyst can continue without rebuilding context.",
        "codeExample": "// Splunk SPL: Exfiltration hunt via outbound/inbound byte ratio + volume + novelty\nindex=network sourcetype=pan:traffic action=allow\n| where NOT cidrmatch(\"10.0.0.0/8\", dest_ip) AND NOT cidrmatch(\"192.168.0.0/16\", dest_ip)\n| stats sum(bytes_out) as bytes_out\n        sum(bytes_in) as bytes_in\n        min(_time) as first_seen\n        count as sessions\n        by src_ip dest_ip dest_port\n| eval ratio = round(bytes_out / (bytes_in + 1), 2)\n| eval mb_out = round(bytes_out / 1048576, 1)\n| where mb_out > 100 AND ratio > 10                       // bulk AND inverted\n// novelty: destination not seen for this src in the prior baseline window\n| search NOT [ inputlookup src_dest_baseline.csv | fields src_ip dest_ip ]\n| sort - mb_out\n| table src_ip dest_ip dest_port mb_out ratio sessions first_seen\n// Then correlate the same src_ip + time window against DLP/CASB alerts.\n// MITRE: T1041 (over C2), T1048 (alt protocol), T1567 (cloud). Off-hours = higher score."
      }
